snippet.textDisplay: Dear god the pedal taverns in Nashville are a nightmare. Story time. I work part time as a security guard for music venues around Nashville and had just finished my shift at Ascend Amphitheater. After signing out I had to walk a block into Nashville (ascend is right next to the Cumberland River) in order to get onto the pedestrian bridge that goes over the river to get to my car. Once I got to the other end of the bridge, but still high up enough that I could see pretty far, I could clearly hear a pedal tavern absolutely blaring, “my neck, my back”, driving through the empty parking lot of Nissan stadium at midnight.

snippet.textDisplay: I worked in Nashville two weeks out of every month for the last three years and tended to stay on the West End within walking distance of the Hattie Bs in that neighborhood. I treated myself to it one every couple of  months always buying online and taking away my order back to the hotel because, wow, the lines. I love it. But in Nashville this is the white folks hot chicken. I never got over to Prince's the original. Only because it required a Lyft ride. Don't get me wrong. I love love love Hattie Bs, But the original is Prince's. Run by the niece of the philanderer whose wife made him scorching hot chicken when he came in after one of his adventures. Instead of revenge it became a sensation.  This chicken is no joke. I always get a side of pickles because that vinegar brine helps cool the burn.

snippet.textDisplay:
Looks yummy!
If you want to make a “Popeyes” style sandwich with it, make a sauce of mayo, hot sauce (I used Tabasco) with some onion powder, garlic powder, paprika, salt, cayenne and black pepper. Spread on a bun and add some pickle chips. Sweet or dill chips for burgers are excellent for this, and help balance the heat from the chicken and sauce.
Seriously, give it a try. It’s amazing.
